TextChange: Today, are your living out your childhood dream job, or did you pursue a different career? If you chose the latter, I envy you. Childhood dream jobs may include becoming a firefighter, a teacher, a doctor, or a scientist, to new a few. As children, we looked to our role models and the things that inspired us. We wanted these jobs because they seemed cool and it was what we wanted to do. \n

Some believe that happiness comes by pursuing their dreams and their own personal goals. Others believe that people are happy only when they have their minds fixed on some goal other than their own happiness. Accordingly, happiness comes when people focus on the happiness of others or on the improvement of humanity. Aiming at something other than their own happiness, they find happiness along the way.\n

Growing up, you realize how being unable to pursue your goals and dreams is difficult. Finances, resources, time, and other circumstances get in the way. The majority of individuals are unable to pursue their dreams and achieve their personal goals in retirement - if they reach retirement. \n

In corporate America, individuals focus on the happiness of others. Employees worry about impressing and keeping their boss happy for fear of being fired. As a result, free time to dream and rest turn into over-time.\n

Today, are you living out your childhood dream job? Or, did you pursue a different career? If you are the latter, I envy you. Childhood dream jobs including a firefighter, a teacher, a doctor, a scientist, to name a few. As children, we looked to our role models and that which inspired us. We wanted these jobs because they seemed cool. At the time , our parents or guardians smiled at our dreams. \n

If you are the former, I am with you.

Have you ever carried out a favor for someone else? Perhaps you donated to charity by running a marathon that donated funds for cancer. Or, you obtained straight A's on your report card so you would receive recognition and a prize.
Arguably, focusing on something other than yourself sparks motivation and happiness, but is the feeling of happiness overtaken with the feeling of pride in doing something for someone else? \n
Are people more likely to be happy if they focus on their personal goals or on the happiness of others?\n
